name: Baladin Isaac

desc: Feels like it's missing something. The bitterness is there but sadly no great flavour behind that. Really high levels of sediment as well. A rare miss from fox hat
name: Fox hat red pelt

desc: Can't pick out the peanut butter but there's a great smoothness that comes with it. Kind of wish they just called it a stout and didn't get my hopes up
name: Belching beaver peanut butter stout

desc: Very refreshing which is exactly what I need on a 40C day. Certainly has a taste of tonic, in a good way. I'm torn between loving this as an easy drinking beer and missing more interesting flavours

desc: Has a beautiful hazy golden color. Starts off a bit yeasty but that fades quickly. Almost no lingering bitterness and there's a slight tangy flavour but there's just too something that seems wrong

desc: A tad harsh but a decent floral aroma. Just the right level of flavour for a pale ale to be interesting and easily sessionable. Sadly I only have the 1
name: Brewdog hop fiction pale ale

desc: A balance between a wit and a sour but perhaps too bitter to sit in that range. Fairly easy drinking but not as refreshing as I was hoping. Hard to pick out any flavours

desc: My saison dry hopped with lemon grass. Has an interesting little tang to it. Has much less of a Belgian flavour than the #16 and is more rounded. Still more of a slow drinking winter beer than a refreshing saison
name: Skorubrew #17

desc: Easy drinking but with enough flavour to keep me happy
name: Wild yak pacific ale

desc: It's decent, slightly better than I expected. Not too much hop forward flavour. Going well with dinner
name: Koshihikari echigo

desc: Sweet drinking. Probably a little bit too drunk to fully appreciate this
name: Modus operandi session IPA

desc: I'm hungover and right now this is a massive help. Super easy drinking and right on point for a pilsner
name: Kalnapils pilsner

desc: Surprisingly smooth. Not actually that bitter. It's amazing when you can knock off this amount of booze and still feel like it's a fresh beer
name: Golden road wolf mother triple IPA

brewery: Cervecería Mexicana S. de R.L. de C.V. (Tecate)
desc: A sweet smell with a mild stoutiness. Not super exciting but on point for what is and easy to drink
name: Beer of the dead porter

desc: A little bit too heavy on the farmhouse sharpness for me
name: Golden road saison citron

desc: Medium bitterness and heavy on earthy hops. Good middle of the road IPA
name: Extra hop sauce

desc: Interesting colour, I expected it to be a little more sour. It's mild and easy drinking but sits in a place that's not quite my thing
name: Young Henry's mulberia

desc: Once you get past the salt there's a touch of melon. The only issue is the more you drink the thirstier your get. But it delivers everything it promises
name: Willie the boatman salty melon

desc: A little too dry for my liking
name: Australian new world pilsner

desc: Like Nutella in beer form but also not at all. Nutty, chocolaty, smooth and oh so dark. Rather filling for a beer which makes me happy with one despite it being a tasty beer
name: La Sirène praline

desc: Not sure what's in this IPA but it's all wrong. Like really difficult to drink
name: Newstead two to the valley

brewery: Cervecería Mexicana S. de R.L. de C.V. (Tecate)
desc: I don’t think my cat isn’t too happy about being used as a prop. There’s a nice warmingness but it goes down pretty easy. No great hoppyness but it’s well balanced
name: Beer of the dead hop on or die

desc: One of the most over carbonated beers I’ve found. Took forever for the head to reach drinkable levels. Smells of some slightly funky yeast and that carries though to the taste but the flavour is mild otherwise. It’s in a spot where it’s almost amazing but doesn’t quite manage to get there
name: Stelle and Strisce

desc: Unfortunately this beer has a sourness that just tastes off. Like rotten fruit or beer mixed with shit wine
name: Buxton Pic Tor

desc: A nice bit of hops with low bitterness. I've never been a fan of XPAs before but I really see how this works as a style. Also the can is smiling at me
name: Balter XPA

desc: A little darker than I planned but still red. Has a yeasty, Belgian smell which fades and lets the smokiness through. But the hero here is the taste. The smoked malt and rye add an element that you don’t normally find. The lower bitterness means this flavour doesn’t linger which keeps you wanting more. The Belgian yeast rounds the flavour further and the 7.5% gives a slight warming sensation. My best homebrew yet
name: Skorubrew #19 red rye IPA

desc: A little biscuity but otherwise a pretty plain and tasteless beer
name: Wrong side brewing pale ale

desc: Mild for a Belgian ale which makes it easy drinking but also leaves me wanting more. And I mean more in the beer, not wanting another. Not that I would complain
name: Brew by numbers Belgian pale

desc: Has a weird after taste that doesn't belong in this beer. There's something interesting as well but altogether it doesn't quite work
name: Boatrocker pale ale

desc: Piney but lacking citrus to round it out. Gets better as I drink but it almost has a wheat flavour which I wasn't what I was hoping for
name: Batch trippy hippy citra xpa

desc: Not as much caramel as I hoped. It's definitely there but you have to search. It's an easy drinking brown with a little bit extra and I wish I had some more
name: Doctors orders saccharophobic

desc: Fairly sessionable but not as good as other things I've had from them. But perhaps I've just hit the point where I've had enough beer for the night
name: Yeastie boys bigmouth

desc: Fairly dry with a little hint of malt in the back. A little stronger than most lagers which is nice. Easy drinking but it’s not an exciting beer
name: Carling black label

desc: Nice selection of hops. Perhaps just a little too harsh for my liking but still easy drinking and full of flavour. Feel like I could drink a lot of these
name: 4 pines Keller door hop hash XPA

desc: Has a really lovely spicyness which gives this beer a little more flavour than a regular pilsner. Still easy drinking and smooth but with enough depth to keep me happy
name: Pirate life white labs pilsner

desc: Not really what I expect from an IPA but that’s normal for a Belgian IPA. I’m torn between this being an easy and balanced drink and it lacking exciting flavours. There’s a little bit of spiciness as it warms at least
name: Viven Master IPA

desc: It’s lager. Nothing much else to say
name: Castle lager

desc: Really loving rye in beers lately where it’s not overwhelming. Because this isn’t a hoppy beer it’s still the hero
name: Newsteads wastelands red rye IPA

desc: Lager with a slightly richer level of malt than normal
name: Dam burg

desc: Has a really deep flavour. The earthy hops are there but they don’t take away from this being a red ale. Overall it’s really well balanced and easy drinking
name: Kaiju! Hopped out red

desc: Too heavy on the bitterness for my liking and quite piney and resiny. Having a couple would be nice to give me more time to get used to it and pick out the hop flavours over the bitterness
name: Kaiju! Metamorphosis IPA

desc: Heavy and full of flavour. Good mix of hops in the middle of floral and earthy . High starting bitterness but it doesn't linger
name: Kaiju! robohop

desc: Straight away has a saison yeasty tang. More restrained on the hops than I expected from a pale. Light, refreshing and easy to drink, just not what I expected
name: La Sirène Urban Pale

desc: The colour is absolutely beautiful. Smells funky as hell but the taste is much better. Full of a sour fruitiness and reminds me of plums but doesn’t have any off flavours. There’s almost no bitterness and a subtle sweetness to finish
name: Del Borgo Prunus

desc: A great refreshing beer. Malt driven but not to the level of European lagers. Exactly what I expect from a kölsch
name: Colonial draught Kölsch

desc: Resiny and citrus hops. It could almost be an IPA given the ABV and amount of hops. Fairly well rounded overall and the more I drink the more I wish I had another one
name: Liberty brewing yakima monster

desc: Has a mild Belgian yeastiness. Not at all what I expect from an IPA but it’s enjoyable nonetheless. Mild and easy drinking with a slight taste of hops
name: Ridgeway IPA

desc: A lot of flavour for a small beer. Tastes very much like a west coast IPA. My main complaint is that while the bitterness and hops are there the mouthfeel is a bit watery so it doesn’t have the a nice smoothness. Worth a try but I wouldn’t be looking for another
name: Ballast point even keel

desc: I think this is the best berliner weisse I’ve found. Really refreshing and easy drinking with just a slight sourness
name: Nomad Rosie’s summer punch

desc: Expected something light and tasteless. It’s actually quite malty and full of flavour. Still not exciting enough to bring me back
name: Oskar blues beerito

desc: Love the colour I got with this one but not much else. A really yeast driven beer and perhaps too much for my taste
name: Skorubrew #20 witbier

desc: Such a smooth dark beer. Dominated by a rich coffee flavour. I don’t even like coffee but I like this. Not much malt going on. Fairly light on the sweetness but the bitterness also so that’s balances out for me
name: Newstead 21 feet 7 inches

desc: Definitely has a raspberry flavour in there but fairly mild otherwise. Not sour like you might expect from a fruit beer. Interesting concept but could do with some hops to balance the sweetness
name: Wrong side brewing Raspberry pale

desc: I’ve been dying to try out this beer. The hops are all floral and citrus but without any of the bitterness that normally comes with such a hoppy beer. It manages to be refreshing while still packing in tons of flavour. Reminds me a lot of the pirate life pale ale
name: Kaiju! crush

desc: Smells like vanilla and cookies, so much so that the initial bitterness is a shock. Seems like an attempt to mix the flavours of an ice cream with beer, which is obviously difficult so it’s a complex beer that just manages to hold together

desc: The bottle kicked off the experience by frothing all over the table. Definitely smells like lime but I can’t taste it
name: Moondog splice of heaven

desc: Really easy drinking for a red ale, mellow as hell. Usually I love big beers full of flavour but this is a perfect easy drinking craft beer
name: Valhalla Ziggy

desc: All pine and floral on the nose. A little resiny in taste but not to the point where it overbalances the other flavours. Definitely a hop forward bitter DIPA

desc: Clear but full of particles. There's something odd in this beer, not bad just a flavour I can't pick out. Bitterness is completely overshadowed by the hops, just how I like my IPA
name: Mount pleasant shake your fruity milkshake

desc: A little more bitter than expected. But there's a delicious sweetness that works well. It's moderately hoppy, somewhere in the middle between easy drinking and flavourful
name: Modus operandi pale ale

desc: Loving the haze on this beer. Full of floral and citrus hops with a little bit of pine. It's biter but it balances perfectly. Full of flavour but I could drink a bunch of these
name: Bridge side cut

desc: Not at all what I expected from something labeled as a wheat beer, more like a hoppy pale ale. But I can’t complain because it’s pretty damn good. Manages to be easy drinking at the same time. The kind of beer you could have bunch of
name: Jerkface 9000

desc: Starts off tropical with quite a bit of pineapple going on. But that fades and it has a bit of a Belgian spiciness which I wasn’t expecting. It’s good but I expected more
name: Tropical torpedo

desc: Not as much coconut as I was expected from the name. I would say there’s actually more vanilla than coconut. It’s nicely smooth, but perhaps a little bit overly sweet. Interesting to try but I’m not rushing for another
name: Oskar blues death by coconut

desc: Has a bitterness but it doesn't linger at all. Lots of fresh citrus hops making this full of flavour. Would never guess this has as much alcohol as it does, it's dangerously easy to drink
name: Feral brewing tusk

desc: Mostly malt driven. A little bit of a roasted flavour. It's decent but not that exciting, quite easy to drink though
name: Beer creative Einstein

desc: Looks a lot like a Guinness but it's not as dry so easier to drink. No strong flavours but a decent session beer
name: 4 pines nitro stout

desc: Very orange in color, smells a little like an unpeeled orange but it doesn’t really carry through to the flavour. I like the idea but it doesn’t come together that well
name: Sierra Nevada Sidecar

desc: I can’t pick out any of the dry hop flavours but I’m ok with that because it’s a delicious sour. The kind of sour which gets it right without bothering to worry about hiding it with fruit. It’s hard to say much about this because I don’t have much to compare it to. Definitely worth a try for anyone who feels like experimenting with sours
name: Four winds Nectarous

desc: A little bitter with mostly earthy hops
name: All star session IPA

desc: Your basic flavourless lager except in a giant can. Just what I need right now
name: Žatecky Gus

desc: Quite a lot going on but it's hard to pick out. Both a little smokey and quite creamy. There's a sweetness too but it doesn't fight with the other flavours
name: Doan amaretto

desc: Finally found a beer that lets me understand the dankness of an IPA. The bitterness is high but it’s well rounded. Seems a bit like it has many different styles of hops involved which all come together to give that dank
name: Feral Fanta pants

desc: Definitely a Belgian ale but it’s hard to say if it’s anything more
name: Dageraad Sri Lanka

desc: Super packed with flavour. The bourbon comes through as well as a huge amount of toastyness. Can't taste the booze at all. Still not worth the price
name: Founders KBS

desc: A nice easy drinking mild stout, pretty great example of what a stout should be
name: Founders breakfast stout

desc: Tastes more like a wheat ale than a gose. Not bad but I wanted more
name: Doctors orders electrolyte serum

desc: Really flavourful golden ale full of malty goodness. Not a special beer but a decent staple
name: Dos blockos fuck the rent

desc: Slightly watered down stout. Just doesn't have the creaminess that I want right now

desc: A fairly thin dark ale. The chocolate and orange are fairly mild. Interesting but I probably didn't need a pint

desc: You really get lamington as you swallow just without the sweetness. Powerful but easy drinking. Could have been a bit creamier

desc: Looks like a feminine beer but it definitely isn't. Has a very strong Belgian taste to it. The hibiscus comes through as well. Doesn't have the freshness that I expected

desc: Pretty dank and tasty. The rum comes through but it's really faint
name: Bacchus kraken IPA

desc: Definitely evokes memories of rocky road but the bitterness overpowers a lot of it

desc: Very light. Has almost a slight spicyness
name: Bucket boys This is rice country

desc: Slight toastyness. Like a very thin stout. Easy drinking but lacks depth

desc: Full Belgian flavour but a bit lighter. Has a delicious lingering taste that I can't quite describe. Absolutely smooth with almost no bitterness

desc: Everything about this beer is amazing
name: Blackfont souvenir old ale

desc: Love the creamyness on this beer
name: Batch hopsy mozy nitro IPA

desc: It's a good level of smoke but lacks much else

desc: Good stout which causes no qualms but delivers nothing special

desc: My favourite of the range so far. Clean and crisp

desc: Super smokey, in fact too much for the size of the bottle. It was smooth otherwise so there wasn't much to cover the smokiness

desc: Decent hop aroma but it doesn't come through much in the taste. Fairly smooth for an IPA but it's not enough to save it

desc: Slightly tangy smell and tastes almost like a pilsner. But one with a subtle body and no aftertaste. Good for a hot day
name: Capital coast ale

desc: Fairly easy drinking XPA with a tad of sweetness in the aftertaste. Beautiful golden clarity
name: Big shed Astra XPA

desc: Like the pacific ale but a little ale’y and more floral. Doesn’t evoke the same feelings of carefree bevving
name: Stone and wood cloud catcher

desc: Right from the first mouthful it hits you as a rich unashamedly. It’s actually not too heavy on the coffee side, more with toffee and caramel and slightly burnt flavours. It’s a smooth drink but I’m not sure if I could have many it
name: Prancing Pony Black Ale

desc: Classic sour that’s exactly what you expect. No other big flavours, just a very sour beer. If you like sour beers then give it a try, otherwise you’ll probably be disappointed
name: Temple Dawn

desc: Tastes like a strong English ale but it’s actually pretty low in aldohol. Slight caramel malt taste. Very easy drinking and smooth
name: Barossa valley campfire session

desc: Very unique style of hops and more bitter than I expected. Mostly dry with a very minor sweet after taste. Takes a while to get used to but good at the end
name: Western ridge friendly bison

desc: Seems more like a pilsner or a lager than a golden ale. Middle of the road but lacks anything to make me love it
name: Western ridge summerye

desc: Best served a little warmer to let the roundness of the rye out a little. Interesting to see a more malt driven IPA, though it complements the fairly high bitterness well
name: Sydney Pyrmont rye IPA

desc: Smells fresh but tastes like it’s from the west coast. It’s one to drink slowly
name: Western ridge topaz pride summer

desc: Smells like a nice IPA, then you take a sip and it starts fine and ends up like water. Leaves me questioning why I’m even bothering to have a beer at all. I guess if you want something with just a tinge of hops and not much alcohol then this would be the beer for you
name: Holgate gate keeper

desc: Nice tropical hoppy smell uncharacteristic of a lager. Tastes like a clean crisp lager without much bitterness. Just a little bit of biscuity citrusy goodness to balance it out. Perfect for a hot day
name: Mornington new world lager

desc: I’m not usually a fan of ESB but this one’s pretty good. Reminds me of London ales but much smoother and not like someone put a cigarette in your beer. A little nutty with enough malt to smooth it out
name: Hargreaves hill ESB

desc: Has a very strange tinge to it. Can’t pick what it is, like something that wants to break through but there’s another flavour blocking it. Not for me
name: Young Henry’s afends hemp IPA

desc: I don’t usually like watermelon in beer but this works well with the sourness. I mean, it’s weak enough to be classed as water, but it’s a nice flavoured water
name: Feral watermelon Warhead

desc: So I’m already drunk before opening this can so it’s probably clouding my review of what is a fairly heavy beer. It’s kind of low on the hops but heavy on the malt. Just couldn’t get into this
name: Nomad red nosed reindeer

desc: The head on this looks like dish soap, probably because the beer is flat. Tastes a bit like dirty dishes as well. Gets a bit better as it goes down but never quite good
name: Stockade MR Fruju NEIPA

desc: Fairly plain lager. I’ve had so many winners from this brewery that I thought they would make a lager actually amazing. Has a little bit of a sweet tinge but not much else to make it memorable
name: Green beacon grappler lager

desc: One of the better pilsners I’ve had. It’s distinctively a pilsner but mellow enough to not let that get in the way of being a nice summer beer
name: Boatrocker beer garden pilsner

desc: Standard European pilsner. Smells dry and tastes malty
name: СТАРОЃРАДСКО

desc: Loving this super hoppy punch in the face. Lots of piney, dank hops but no lingering after taste. Going down faster than it should given the strength. Purchase only if you like strong IPAs
name: Blackmans angry reg

desc: It’s an easy drinking lager with a little pilsner malt going on. Would be ok if it wasn’t a mid strength
name: Maat’s session lager

desc: A nice mild pilsner, very German in its simplicity. A good hot weather beer
name: Krombacher pils

desc: Beautiful orange colouring. Surprisingly creamy with lots of zesty flavours and a clean finish
name: Krombacher weizen

desc: A bit of a hearty winter ale, which might not fit the best with an Australian Christmas. Very smooth with malt coming through like toasted bread. I wish I had a few more
name: Stomping grounds wassail ale

desc: Absolutely black beer but only really a little tinge in the taste
name: Krombacher dark

desc: Very dank hops. Can definitely taste the difference with the wet hop
name: Bridge road Hop rain

desc: Sometimes I forget how good a saison can be. That lovely mix of Belgian goodness and summery freshness
name: Saucy Saison

desc: The name suggests they just threw every hip thing into a single beer. It’s surprisingly not an absolute mess. A sweet brown ale with a little hop kick just to top it off. Tasty and very drinkable
name: New England Frederick India brown ale hop cannon

desc: Super mellow stout
name: Bucket boys don’t get caught with stout on your face

desc: Very nice hop balance. Easy drinking and very enjoyable
name: Brick lane hoppy red

desc: Great middle of the road pale ale. Enough hops to give it some flavour without becoming overwhelming and difficult to drink
name: T-Bone pale ale

desc: It’s an ok mid strength
name: Iron house day tripper

desc: Fairly plain pale ale
name: Last rites Horn of diligence

desc: A nice tart ale. One of the better sours I’ve had recently
name: White rabbit Teddywiddler

desc: Looks like sludge. Tastes ok, fairly smooth. Bit funny towards the end. Still not convinced this keg was ok
name: Philter red session ale

desc: Makes me feel like it’s summer just drinking it. It’s not big on hop flavours but it’s enough to deliver the tropical notes that it promises. Maintains a refreshing taste
name: Burleigh twisted palm

desc: Bitter west coast IPA but well done. A good beer to get started with IPA
name: Moo brew IPA

desc: IPA with a little tang at the end
name: Cloudy bay IPA

desc: Solid stout, has a nice creaminess from the whey. If you’re after a straight stout then it’s hard to fault this one
name: Bruny island whey stout

desc: I’m at the brewery on a beautiful day after a long walk but this beer is brining me down a little. It’s just not a pale ale, it’s a lager
name: Cascade pale ale

desc: Standard lager
name: Cascade draught

desc: Nice creamy stout. Makes me happy
name: Shambles Barry white

desc: Really floral IPA. Not too heavy on the bitterness
name: Shambles dances with hops

desc: Delivers well on the promise of fruit
name: T-bone fruit bowl IPA

desc: Well done XPA. Amazed they only do this seasonally given the popularity of the style
name: T-bone XPA

desc: Not really getting much of the pale hoppiness, it’s really just a dark beer. As such it’s ok, but nothing exciting
name: Bruny Island oxymoron

desc: Very easy drinking and well rounded pils. Pretty happy with this
name: Saucy pils

desc: Very fruity pale ale
name: Nomad South Pacific dream

desc: A little bit of a tangy IPA. Not that excited
name: Basement brewhouse cereal offender

desc: Delivers on the zest it promises but the zest seems to give it a bit of a harshness in the back of the throat
name: North end super alpha

desc: A little harsh to start but rounds out. Doesn’t deliver the flavours it promises
name: Prancing pony Zeppelin

desc: Fairly dry for a pale ale. No real hops coming through
name: Brewmanity social beast

desc: Really smooth and full bodied ale. No big flavours but very easy drink. Nice start to my foray into Tasmanian beers
name: Bruny island farm ale

desc: Lacks the creamy finish that I love in a milk stout. Has the rest of what you would expect
name: Iron house milk stout

desc: Mellow without being too hoppy. There’s no big flavours on either side. It’s well balance but not enough to bring me back
name: Warpigs rain of terror black IPA

desc: Solid juicy IPA. Hard to decide whether to savour the taste or smash it down
name: Feral biggie juice

desc: Has a distinctive but mild maltyness but otherwise easy drinking. Lives up to being quite nice beer
name: Uncle Kenny’s wakachangi

desc: Very smooth and refreshing. No strong flavours makes it go down easy
name: Belhaven black

desc: Kind of yeasty. Has rich smells but doesn’t carry through much into the taste
name: Old wives ale horn swatter

desc: Interesting mix of hops and sour. But it’s fairly sweet which brings out the smell of the hops
name: 8 wired hippy Berliner

desc: Nothing really amazing. Expected more
name: Eden phoenix

desc: A bit sour, a bit of lacto but not much hops. Something different about this and really nice
name: Old wives ales lactohop

desc: Slightly yeasty ale. Unexciting
name: Rover Henty st ale

desc: Very nice mix of hops and malt
name: Brewhouse simcoe black ipa

desc: Nice fresh IPA
name: Ballast point fathom IPA

desc: Slightly tangy and very refreshing. Lots of fruit coming through. I can see why this brewery is highly rated
name: Toøl tropical rumble

desc: A little bit bland, but has some citrus notes and easy drinking on a hot day
name: Barossa valley Indian summer session ale

desc: Fairly mild pale ale. Not much on the nose. More of a lager really. In that respect it’s good, but not enough to justify buying a craft beer
name: Bad Shepard Victoria pale ale

desc: Interesting hop profile but not something that would keep me coming back
name: 4 pines in season IPA

desc: Solid DIPA with a nice roundness of flavour. Very smooth for what it is
name: Pact co Tennents peak double ipa

desc: Classic saison with not too much to turn someone off
name: Yullis Hans gropo

desc: Tastes a lot like raspberry cordial. Too much sugar for me. I guess if you don’t like beer but want to get pissed then it would work for you
name: Batch chapeau

desc: Slightly tangy blonde. Hard to drink when it gets warm. Maybe I’m just being mean after drinking pure blonde
name: Steerman blonde

desc: Very plain Australian style lager. No real flavours at all which makes it easy to drink. It was cheap, but not worth going back for another
name: Billy’s lager

desc: It’s a beer filled with super foods and therefore healthy. Red ale flavours mixed with the tartness of berries reminds me a little bit of berocca. Feels both fulfilling and refreshing
name: Barossa Valley vitamin (B)eer

desc: Slightly tart and very refreshing. A little bit hoppy but not much. It’s cheap so I’m giving it a pass on being piss weak
name: Venom refreshing ale

desc: So I opened this bottle expecting another very plain European pilsner. But instead it has really biscuity taste and a huge amount of caramel in the smell. Despite that it’s still fairly light. Quite a unique mass market beer
name: BiP

desc: Very hoppy for a lager but restrained enough to keep it refreshing
name: Newstead golden lager

desc: Very strange to start, doesn’t smell like beer and it’s throwing me off. Taste is rich, sweet, malty and very smooth. A little bit like a mild and sweet whiskey. Still by the end I feel confused as to what I’m drinking. Interesting, but I wouldn’t try it again
name: 3 Ravens blended barleywine

desc: I’ve not seen the term Australian style pale ale before, as far as I can see this is just a lager. In that regard it’s better than mass market Australian lagers, but not enough to make it worth a purchase
name: Coastal One mile pale ale

desc: Most double IPAs are a punch in the face, this is mild and more malt driven. Rich and deep with no lasting flavours. Maybe the most dangerous beer I’ve had. Without knowing what it was you could just keep knocking these down
name: Claire valley double NEIPA

desc: Finished bottling #35 so time for a reward beer. It’s a crisp refreshing drop with just enough citrus hops to make it interesting. Gets better as it goes down
name: Wayward dead dingo

desc: A bit of rich redness with a pronounced bitterness. Smells like a lager but tastes richer
name: Sherpa Himalayan red

desc: It’s mild and refreshing with a hint of hops at the end. Hops are more on the nose than in the mouth
name: Sierra Nevada session IPA

desc: It’s a very rich beverage, but there’s a little toughness that spoils the smoothness
name: Harviestoun old engine oil

desc: Kind of boring. Very west coast IPA
name: Sierra Nevada resilience

desc: Very full bodied IPA. Doesn’t give the fruit flavours it promises. Not something to smash down but great to savour slowly
name: The garden milkshake IPA

desc: Strong bitter double IPA
name: Green beacon uppercut

desc: Fairly mild stout. Was hoping for a bit more body to hold the chocolate and coconut
name: Murray coco hops

desc: So so so much fruit in this fella. If you can handle the bitterness it’s like a glass of beer juice. Delivers exactly what it promises
name: Big shed boozy fruit

desc: Nice fruity IPA, not that special but solid. Easy to drink and given the strength would knock you about easily
name: Slipstream g-force

desc: Nice haze, fruity smell and a fresh taste. Basically just a smooth, easy drinking IPA
name: Brouhaha New England IPA

desc: Great fruity drop. Not too much bitterness so good with food
name: One drop XPA

desc: Really strange flavour that I can’t quite place. It tastes strong but there’s not actually that much alcohol. Takes a bit of getting used to. As I finally finish the last warm dregs I work out what the taste is, it’s a tiny hint of super tennents. Despite that, it’s not too bad
name: Slipstream Sabro strong pale ale

desc: Takes about 5 minutes just to settle.  It’s a slightly sour red but very mild in most ways. By the end I want more, but I don’t want to wait for it to settle again
name: Batch sky rocket in flight

desc: Kind of like spoiled wheat. Really strong smell which just doesn’t seem right. Can’t tell if this is off or just bad. Regardless, not a good beer
name: Basement brewhouse pilot #8 Brel

desc: A sour which doesn’t mess it up with too much sugar. The mango comes through but it’s properly transformed into a beer version. Refreshing
name: Hope mango sour

desc: Peach not really coming through, it’s just a bit of a bland sour. Nothing to keep me coming back
name: Peach sauce

desc: Plain pale ale. A little too bitter for my liking without much else. Tasted better while drinking around friends
name: Spotty dog Portland pale ale

desc: Lots of floral notes. Doesn’t taste as strong as it is. Leaves a nice warmth in the stomach. Would actually be easy to get through a pint. Dangerously good
name: Panhead the vandal

desc: Slightly rounded lager. Easy drinking not much else to say
name: One drop Botany Bay lager

desc: It’s an ok red but only good enough for my left hand
name: Basement brewhouse red right hand

desc: Decent IPA with good dank bite. Seems a little thin and missing some roundness
name: Mountain goat hello humanoid

desc: Almost creamy on the tip of the tongue with deliciousness all the way through
name: Basement brewhouse nikolaj

desc: Bit more of a particulate haze than a real one, but maybe that’s my fault for forgetting it in the bottom of a box. A little bit tangy with a light mix of hops
name: Sierra Nevada Hazy little thing IPA

desc: Smells like vanilla and chocolate and so rich. But then you come to the taste and it just blows you away. You get both the chilli and the smoke are there but perfectly subtle so that they add to the beer without overwhelming it.  Leaves a lovely sense of warming inside and a beautiful sweetness on the palette/10
name: Dainton Matchstyx

desc: It’s got the hops and the kick of a NEIPA with a nice little bit of sweetness and a citrus tang. Smells good, looks good, tastes good
name: Barossa Valley NAIPA

desc: Brew day finished, time for a beer. Really creamy stout due to the nitro but tastes a little bit overly bitter and doesn’t have much else flavour wise. That said it’s a good straightforward stout
name: Balter handsome elvis

desc: Super dark and very stouty. Nothing special but a very solid flavour
name: Hop nation karma

desc: Comes off a little sweet and a little spicy
name: Hop nation buzz

desc: Very mild sour. Good refreshing beer for a hot day. Too bad it’s winter. Very smooth and well crafted
name: Kaiju tapestry of chaos

desc: Kind of plain. Very inoffensive and easy to drink but nothing exciting
name: Ekim after battle

desc: Fairly standard IPA, but gotta love that can
name: Deschutes fresh haze

desc: Pretty solid milk stout. Easy drinking  and well rounded
name: Brouhaha milk stout

desc: I don’t mind a bit of chilli in a beer but this is taking it over the top. My lips are stinging. Somehow leaves the flavour of corn chips in my mouth. An interesting experience, but not one I would repeat
name: Batch señor spicy

desc: Lots of floral smells with a lot of hop freshness. Somehow this gets a bit lost in the taste, the bitterness comes through strong and overwhelms the rest
name: Deep creek misty miyagi

desc: Lots of banana. Very easy to drink. Great hefeweizen, middle of the road. Upset I haven’t had this sooner
name: 4 pines hefeweizen

desc: It’s a decent imperial. Fairly dead on for the style without any extras. Alcohol comes through a little strong but then it is a strong beer
name: 4 pines queen bee IV

desc: Good amount of coffee to beer ratio. Not enough caffeine to wake me up. Pretty good drinking
name: Coastal little street coffee milk stout

desc: Tart citrus smell with a bitter taste that doesn’t have any strong hop flavours. Like a west coast IPA mixed with a little bit of a sour red
name: Moon dog thunder lips

desc: With all the focus on east coast IPAs lately I forget how good a west coast IPA can be. Not too much dank pine in the hops nor too bitter with a strong floral aroma. Surprisingly easy to drink
name: Hemingways endeavour

desc: Smells like boozy maple syrup. I shouldn’t be eating at the same. Outside of that it’s a good imperial and I want more
name: Rocks 2015 Russian imperial stout

desc: Fairly mellow IPA but enough to keep it interesting
name: Thunder road Big’N juicy

desc: Smells really mild and not much in the way of hops in the taste. The most prominent taste is really the alcohol. It’s not as bad as that might sound, it does fit together well and leaves me feeling happy and warm inside
name: Hope Jet black IIIPA

desc: Really good balance between amber and IPA flavours. Lots of malt and bitterness and a crisp smell
name: Ekim berserker amber IPA

desc: Seems a little too bitter for an XPA
name: Hemingway’s Doug’s courage

desc: Kind of yeasty, tastes cheap and not well put together at all. But it’s still beer
name: Moon dog old mate

desc: Like a mild orange chocolate mixed with beer. Could probably do with a bit more sweetness but good all round
name: Badlands dark side of orange

desc: Leaves the taste of sugar donuts on the tip of your tongue. Like dunking donuts in coffee, but not good coffee. Interesting but I only want one
name: Wayward coffee and donuts

desc: Lots of sweetness coming through both in smell and taste. Doesn’t really seem like a beer, but who cares. Like beer mixed with champagne and raspberries
name: Frenchies rosé brut IPA

desc: Creaminess from the lactose comes through strong and there’s something else in there that I can’t pick. Not too full on despite the strength. Feeling very happy
name: Shenanigans purple haze

desc: The amount of aroma coming off this is amazing, like smelling a fresh pineapple🍍. Taste is completely smooth and the bitterness is barely detectable. Even with food all the taste comes through
name: Hope tropical NEIPA

desc: So strange to see this much flavour in what is essentially a light beer. Like weak coffee with a hint of oats
name: McLeod’s last light

desc: Quite clean and crisp with just a little malt that keeps it interesting
name: Brooklyn summer ale

desc: Kind of a pilsner taste
name: Struman’s lager

desc: Tastes a bit like a pilsner with a hint of cigarettes. Not as awful as that my sound, but not a beer I would look for
name: Bad shepherd vic ash pilsner

desc: Kind of a strange mix. Gets better as it warms otherwise the bitterness is a bit harsh
name: Mornington larrikin

desc: Reminds me of a chilli beer but there’s no heat. Interesting but I don’t want another
name: Wolf of the willow Jalisco sour

desc: Just amazing from the first sip. Full of hops and quite bitter
name: Garage project DFA

desc: This beer would not stop foaming. Like a really light Belgian ale. Very enjoyable
name: Garage project heels to Jesus

desc: Really mellow. Love these well made Belgian beers. Almost no hops, all malt focused
name: Mokke Bruin

desc: Almost lagerish, or maybe my last beer was just too strong. Easy drinking but ultimately uninteresting
name: Batch Tasman tango

desc: Only a little bit of raisin which is a good balance with the light brown ale flavours
name: Young Henry’s rumming with the devil

desc: Surprisingly light for a double IPA but doesn’t have anything to win you over
name: Young Henry’s double drop

desc: Seems more like a malty IPA than a pale ale
name: Pirate life north west pale

desc: Easy drinking lager
name: Holtland

desc: Nice amount of citrus and not too much bitterness leads to a well rounded pale
name: Fixation squish

desc: Creamy body and a rich stout flavour
name: Sierra Nevada stout

desc: Very strange, expected a brown but it’s more of a slightly sour pale. Not so much bad, just not to style
name: Moondog how now brown cacao

desc: Great amount of flavour for a lighter beer. Perfect introduction to a hazy ipa
name: Lervig hazy days

desc: A dark hoppy beer. Well made but nothing special
name: Sauce o ho! Cascadia

desc: Beautiful haze and a smell that you get from across the table. Mild and juicy
name: Balter hazy DC

desc: Really wasn’t sure what to expect from this one, and still struggling as I finish it. The brut yeast mellows out the bitterness but also kills the hop flavours. Nothing in it really makes me want to find it again
name: New England bubbles in the orchard

desc: I really like the pickle mixed with the gose
name: Sailors grave crystal healing

desc: Standard IPA with a little bit of dank hops
name: Moondog Edie’s IPA

desc: The lacto really comes through and works well with the lemon. Not at all like a beer, more like traditional lemonade
name: Garage project muse

desc: Fairly standard sour meant for non beer drinkers
name: Deep creek Aloha

desc: Pours beautiful and clear. The smell is all Belgian farmhouse but the taste is more like a pale so it becomes a great blend of both. A good one to either savour or skull
name: La sirène season ale

desc: Alcohol and barley are the only tastes that come through. And I wouldn’t say that it balances out that well. It just doesn’t make me happy
name: Little bang Galacotopus

desc: Surprising to see so much packed into a beer with so little alcohol. Very well balanced porter, simple and drinkable
name: Buxton brewery gatekeeper

desc: Very mild for a double IPA, which isn’t to say its a mild beer, but just not as much punch as you might expect. Which just happened to be what I was after as I cooked dinner so I’m very happy with the flavour and a little bit tipsy
name: Sauce the DIPA formally known as

desc: A little bit more bitter than I think it should be which covers up some of the juicyness
name: Deschutes lil squeezy

desc: Very dark for a lager and strangely mild in flavour. Reminds me a little bit of an English hand pump bitter
name: Bridge road nitro mountain lager

desc: Lots of orange coming through which is interesting but not balanced as it should be
name: Akasha east NEIPA

desc: The vanilla doesn’t come through very strong due to high bitterness and not much sweetness
name: Yullis coffee nerd

desc: Quite a bit of bit for a pale ale but your get used to it quickly. Well named because it sits well as a standard beer
name: Wayward everyday ale

desc: Medium level west coast IPA. No big hop flavours coming past the bitterness but it’s what you expect from an IPA
name: Wayward IPA

desc: Strange that a hop thief beer would taste so malt driven. It comes off a lot like a cheap European lager
name: James squire hop theif 9

desc: Not too malty like many pilsners. Like a lager with just a little bit extra flavour
name: Wayward pilsner

desc: Very lightly hopped pale ale. Great sessionable beer
name: Mountain goat very enjoyable beer

desc: Too harsh for what it is
name: Coopers 2019 vintage

desc: Light on bitterness with a pine and tropical finish. Gets a little rough as it warms but I guess I should just drink faster
name: Akasha captain famish

desc: Beautifully sweet and nutty brown ale. That balance where bitterness and sweetness work together perfectly
name: Big shed frankenbrown

desc: Smells a lot of orange but only comes through a little in the taste. Kind of a mellow IPA with a little tang. Very easy drinking
name: Green beacon the whaler

desc: Fairly dry and easy drinking ale. A little touch of fruity hops but not enough to make it interesting
name: Coopers mild ale

desc: Good amount of pineapple but not much mango. Strong bitterness but the citrus makes it easy drinking. It’s a nice NEIPA but there’s a lot better out there
name: 4 pines mango pineapple NEIPA

desc: Mix between a European malty lager and an Australian dry. It’s not too bad, pretty well crafted, but lacking any strong flavours
name: Two suns

desc: The fruit gives it a lot of tang but kind of masks the stout flavours even though the smell is there. Takes a lot of getting used to but even at the end I don’t think it works
name: Toøl mr blue

desc: Smells like being in a citrus orchard in bloom next to a Belgian brewery. I literally started drooling while smelling this. It’s like someone finally got a Belgian IPA right. Too much bitterness to have with food but a beer like this should be enjoyed by itself
name: Garage project hippity dippity

desc: Who makes a pilsner this strong? And why was Metallica involved? And it’s a decent pilsner, but with a slight harshness
name: Stone enter night

desc: Decent hoppy IPA. Sufficiently juicy and not too heavy
name: Hop nation dreamfeed

desc: Very rich and creamy with a lot of chocolate. Not getting much peanut butter but I think it’s just adding to the creaminess. Very low on bitterness. A great beer for a slow drink
name: Garden brewery chocolate & peanut butter stout

desc: One of the first double red ales I’ve had. The extra malt balances nicely against the additional alcohol and hops making it a good rounded beverage
name: Two birds double sunset

desc: Good sweet brown ale, has a little bit of smoke in there which doesn’t really fit. Overall doesn’t go down that smoothly
name: Willie the boatman rubi brown

desc: Heavy bitter west coast IPA
name: Maui big swell

desc: Exactly as the name says, a lemon lime bitters as a beer. I do love bold flavour choices like this but balanced enough to be easy drinking
name: Sauce lemon and lime bitterness units

desc: Solid middle of the road stout
name: Little creatures the fuggle is real

desc: I mostly just bought this for the handle on the bottle. It’s a fairly normal malty beer, but has just has a little tang of something else
name: Three hills ALE

desc: Delivers a good bunch of dank hops. Easy drinking and full of booze and flavour
name: Chur hashtag hops

desc: This beer is already winning due to the amazing bottle. Apart from that it’s a fairly average wheat beer
name: Estrella Damm Inedit

desc: Really interesting flavour that’s hard to place. Like an XPA with a dash of sweetness. A lot of flavour with very little alcohol
name: Yeastie boys hot space

desc: Very hoppy APA, wasn’t expecting it but exactly what I wanted
name: Yullis Matt Steele

desc: Like beer with a little bit of extra alcohol. No hops and not much malt. Seems like a good winter beer
name: Red hill wee heavy

desc: Delivers exactly what it promises. The malt is a bit overridden by the bitterness of the hops but that’s to be expected. Solid middle of the road beer
name: Pirate life hoppy amber

desc: That’s some powerful punch in the face unadulterated west coast hops. Don’t see this much lately so it’s a refreshing change
name: Little bang double west coast IPA

desc: Great yet creepy can art. A lot nuttier than your usual APA which gives this beer a unique signature that is often lacking in craft beers looking to appeal to everybody. Would definitely choose this again
name: Little bang beard fiction

desc: Lightly hopped pale ale with a little extra booze. It’s what you expect from a strong pale but it’s not that exciting
name: Hawkers Circus OZ

desc: Not too strong on the sourness which I like. More of a refreshing light zesty beer
name: Chateu du tasman into the lime light

desc: Strangely sweet and tangy for a brown. Takes a bit of getting used to and not particularly special
name: Fathom belgian style brown

desc: A mostly piney IPA. Has that perfect level of heavyness for an IPA. Not too bitter to have with food
name: Akasha cryo IPA

desc: Doesn’t taste as fruity as it looks, just has a little tang and otherwise it’s a fairly plain IPA
name: Thunder road dark and creamy

desc: Really rich and does remind me of cake. I feel like I’m not devoting enough attention to this and am missing some flavours. Still nice
name: Moondog cake hole

desc: Very creamy XPA. Exactly what you expect and nothing else
name: Foxhat heavy handed XPA

desc: It’s good but nothing to write home about
name: Modus operandi Pangea

desc: Very nice mix of hops that brings nothing to the front but melds together
name: Brewhouse echo flare

desc: Seems very unexciting. Like’s it’s almost great, but just ends up average
name: Garage project amber ale

desc: Fairly mild porter with a very nutty smell to it, but not really any coconut. Overall enjoyable and easy to drink
name: Thunder road coconut porter
